        <h2 class="title"><a href="/archives/000083.html">Native games for native casinos?</a></h2>    <span class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Mon, 2004-05-10 06:46.</span>
    <span class="taxonomy"><ul class="links inline"><li class="first last taxonomy_term_8"><a href="/archives/cat_inventions.html" rel="tag" title="" class="taxonomy_term_8">Inventions</a></li>
</ul></span>
    <div class="content"><p>Whenever I see a First Nation's (That's the Canadian politically corect term for Indians) Casino, I have a cynical thought along the lines of "ah, the great Indian tradition of video poker."</p>
<p>So here's a good idea for folks in the gambling machine industry:  Track down some <a href="http://www.nativetech.org/games/index.php" rel="nofollow">traditional native games</a> that can be turned into gambling games on machines.  Make machines to play them.</p>
<p>Sure, nobody plays these games any more, not even the Indians.  But while everybody understands the financial attraction of the tribes using their special sovereignty to make a bundle with casinos, I suspect many would jump at the chance to offer a game with even limited origins in their own traditions.</p>
<p>At first, gamblers would be confused at new games, but they are remarkably adept at learning, especially with a little marketing.  In particular, just provide better odds to introduce the games.  Games like "Bowl and Dice" which are random, could easily be converted to slot-machine style games.</p>
<p>Of course this is a heavily regulated industry so a random person can't just enter it on a whim, so I cast this idea out for those already in that business.</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links inline"><li class="first blog_usernames_blog"><a href="/blog/brad" title="Read brad&#039;s latest blog entries." class="blog_usernames_blog">brad&#039;s blog</a></li>
