        <h2 class="title"><a href="/archives/000077.html">New law on semiconductor growth</a></h2>    <span class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Thu, 2004-04-29 12:54.</span>
    <span class="taxonomy"><ul class="links inline"><li class="first taxonomy_term_19"><a href="/archives/cat_best_of_blog.html" rel="tag" title="Blog postings that have been most popular, or which have said things I really wanted to say." class="taxonomy_term_19">Best Of Blog</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_3"><a href="/archives/cat_futurism.html" rel="tag" title="" class="taxonomy_term_3">Futurism</a></li>
<li class="last taxonomy_term_16"><a href="/archives/cat_technology.html" rel="tag" title="" class="taxonomy_term_16">Technology</a></li>
</ul></span>
    <div class="content"><p>In 1965, Gordon Moore of intel published a paper suggesting that the number of transistors on a chip would double every year.  Later, it was revised to suggest a number of 18 months, which became true in part due to marketing pressure to meet the law.</p>
<p>Recently, Intel revised the law to set the time at two years.</p>
<p>So this suggests a new law, that the time period in Moore's Law doubles about every 40 years.</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links inline"><li class="first blog_usernames_blog"><a href="/blog/brad" title="Read brad&#039;s latest blog entries." class="blog_usernames_blog">brad&#039;s blog</a></li>
