        <h2 class="title"><a href="/archives/000072.html">New word: Spamigation</a></h2>    <span class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Thu, 2004-04-22 17:35.</span>
    <span class="taxonomy"><ul class="links inline"><li class="first taxonomy_term_19"><a href="/archives/cat_best_of_blog.html" rel="tag" title="Blog postings that have been most popular, or which have said things I really wanted to say." class="taxonomy_term_19">Best Of Blog</a></li>
<li class="last taxonomy_term_14"><a href="/archives/cat_random_ideas.html" rel="tag" title="" class="taxonomy_term_14">Random Ideas</a></li>
</ul></span>
    <div class="content"><p>Spamigation:  The abuse of bulk legal action.  Filing lawsuits in bulk (as in the RIAA filesharing lawsuits or DirecTV smartcard lawsuits) without taking care to assure all defendants are actually at fault.   As such, some defendants are bound to be entirely innocent, but this doesn't matter because you don't really plan to take any to trial.</p>
<p>Can also be used for threats of legislation, when sending out cease and desist and other threatening letters is bulk, because it's easier to bulk threaten than to research.   Possible alternate spelling: Spammigation.</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links inline"><li class="first blog_usernames_blog"><a href="/blog/brad" title="Read brad&#039;s latest blog entries." class="blog_usernames_blog">brad&#039;s blog</a></li>
